description.narrative: Child Protection service providers are able to deliver quality and timely child protection services, including referrals to other services at all levels., which contributes to Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023 all girls and boys, including adolescents in all settings, are protected from violence, neglect, abandonment and exploitation.

title.narrative: Child Protection service providers are able to deliver quality and timely child protection services, including referrals to otherservices at all levels.

description.narrative: Child Protection service provision has grown progressively in Rwanda despite the challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic. UNICEF key inputs include financial and technical assistance to strengthen the coordination and service delivery capacity of the child protection workforce comprising 34 professionals, 29,674 IZU and the justice workforce. Training on child protection case management was provided to the entire professional workforce and a pilot inclusive de-institutionalization approach has progressed well in two districts, coupled with workforce capacity development initiatives. Short courses in Justice for Children were finalized and rolled out, reaching 288 practitioners (43 per cent female).; | Status:Met | As-of Date:30/12/2021
